The first virtual operator will reach the Czech Republic from this year.
Maybe
Per the mobile phone market in the Czech Republic is quite mature and our operators offer almost all services as their partners in Western Europe.
There still is something missing – a virtual operator that obliges the traditional to lower the price.
It may not be missing for a long time.
The fact that Czech operators belong to the most expensive in Europe we have already written many times on Mobil.cz.
In the end, it has also been confirmed by ČTÚ, which noted that the price of SMS is higher from us than in the rest of the Union.
After the European Commission’s latest steps in the field of roaming rates regulation, a paradox situation may be created – for some Czechi mobile operators customers, SMS will cost less from abroad than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, the lack of competition that would really want to start the fight .
It may sound absurd, also there we have three mobile networks and coverage much above 100%.
Instead, mobile telephony operators like to laugh at the fact that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this sense often emphasizes the head of the Czech Telecommunications Council (ČTÚ) Pavel Dvořák, who in the past some times expressed that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It’s true that the traditional operator with its own network probably no longer has many possibilities. (the rest might be difficult now to find other frequencies).
But there’s still another option – the virtual operator.
Just the entry into the market of virtual operators led to a remarkable decline in prices, to which traditional operators would then have to react.
At the same time, even before the entrance of bears such as Tesko Mobile and Virgin Mobile to the market, sounds similar to us sounded in Britain.
However, it has been shown that the place for such operators exists and that they can really succeed.
At the end of the examples we don’t have to go too far.
In February of this year we informed you of the arrival of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just a half year this operator has managed to acquire more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest local operator.
At the same time, behind Mobilking is the financial group Penta to which in the Czech Republic belongs, among others, U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more concrete group-setting.
To be able to operate effectively, there are many fewer customers enough than a traditional operator.
It is not behind, that is, relatively high costs for the creation, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
So in the world virtual operators usually present at a low cost, offer calls and SMS at a low price, which is often in balance with the most restricted service offer.
Thus, for example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS that costs at least half compared to its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows can be a fairly good move even the bet on a group-setting not recently.
This operator targets to say so specifically about men.
“Real men choose the Mobilking operator that they like and that they can trust,” says David Seibertz, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company that produces this virtual operator.
It’s hard to say if you can also say a similar concept from us as in Poland.
Miroslav Čepický, a spokesman for Vodafone, said: “The Czech market is relatively small for a fragmented approach, on which the majority of virtual operators are based.
Moreover, from the point of view of services it is relatively saturated.”
In the Czech Republic there is no possibility, said mobile network operators
But it seems almost certain that if there will ever be an operator in the Czech Republic it will not be the Mobilking.
“We’re talking about the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic negotiations don’t have many expectations.
The expansion of Mobilking will take place rather in the other countries of our area," said in a telephone dialogue for Mobile.cz Jana Studničková, the press spokesman of the financial group Penta.
So he indirectly confirmed that the current operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not very favorable to this thought.
Instead, they try to do everything because you don’t create any potential competitor.
For a while it has not hidden its interest in the launch of a virtual operator, the GTS Novera group that would like to take another step to become a real competitor of Telefónika O2 in the field of business customers.
“We have a great interest in being able to offer our customers not only fixed services but also mobile telecommunications.
First it is better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile network operators.
We’ve already managed to progress in negotiations with some of them,” said Pavel Kaidl, a spokesman for the group.
Maybe better times will come.
From non-official information it turns out that the first virtual operator will probably have it by the end of the year.
For now, around its creation there is an impenetrable wall of silence.
“At this point we don’t believe that in the Czech market there is room for the creation of a full-time virtual operator.
The Czech market, unlike other markets, is very specific.
Until now, no subject with a complex and serious project has addressed us," he said in his statement to Mobil.cz Vlastimil Sršeň of the press section of Telefònika O2.
The specificity of the Czech market is also applied by other operators.
T-Mobil’s press spokeswoman Martina Kemrová adds in a rare agreement with the O2 statement: “For now we have not noticed any vital and profitable commercial project for both, on which it is possible to continue to build.”
And he adds: "On the T-Mobil network will hardly appear a virtual operator by the end of the year.
At this point we have already had to have a concrete agreement on the table, so that it could be considered at the horizon.”
Vodafone focuses on achieving its 3G license requirements.
Miroslav Čepický adds: “We are open to the negotiations of potential virtual operators, especially in the field of expenditure and infrastructure sharing.
We consider this, from the point of view of customers, the most productive.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this field is to find a partner to build a common network for fast mobile internet.”
The competent authorities – with the complex operators
The attitude of mobile telephone operators can be easily understood, the entrance of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would lead to a decrease in prices and thus a decrease in profits.
Why then facilitate the rise of such a competitor?
The trouble around the creation of U:fon testifies that when the operators hold a thing they know how to remove from the same side.
There is a great pressure on ČTÚ during the creation period of U:fon towards the company of T-Mobile.
This is testified by public access information from the website of ČTÚ.
But now just U:fon serves as a topic for which not accept the virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová noted: “The competitive environment of the mobile phone market has been slightly enhanced above all with the entrance of the fourth mobile operator to the market.
As for the type of mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that the entrance of another competitor would put high demands on him and, above all, on his services.”
However, the attitude of mobile telephone operators is quite surprising the complete disinterest by the Czech regulatory bodies.
It is not just the attitude of the ČTÚ that unfortunately in the Czech Republic – unlike Britain and other developed countries – has no competence to interfere with economic competition.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
This, however, has taken its typical position.
The entrance of the virtual operator to the mobile market would be possible after the conclusion of the necessary infrastructure rental agreement between the mobile operator and the virtual operator was made.
No such contract has been concluded so far because the offer of potential buyers probably has not been interesting enough for traditional operators,” said Kristián Chalupa, of the UOHS Foreign Relations section, in response to our question.
A such statement by the representatives of the operators may not be surprising.
Instead, by the office that must defend the interests of consumers and on the other hand take care of the fact that no one takes advantage of its position on the market, it is more than a delicate deal.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Outside where virtual operators commonly operate, we can notice that their entry into the market has contributed to the lowering of prices for mobile phone services."
But of course the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and the lowering of prices do not belong to ÚOHS interests.
Really shocking in the whole situation is the almost exciting harmony of these three operators resulting from their reactions.
The question of whether it really is only a coincidence, comes by itself.
Just as the same price of the gasoline for all gasoline is the result of coincidence and competitive struggle.
“The section has not found signs of anti-competitive behavior regarding this fact and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
No operator has a dominant position, so it has no corresponding greater responsibility for its behavior on the market.
The necessary tools for the opening of the mobile network market for virtual operators may also lack the telecommunications regulator,” Chalupa said in a statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of the many controversial points.
Of course, there is the analysis of the relevant markets developed by ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications are the only market from the point of view of economic competition.
In such a market, of course, no Czech operator has a dominant position.
But some legal experts offer another approach – for the creation of a virtual operator, the agreement of the network operator is always necessary.
And the mobile operator has – finally logically – the monopoly of its network.
So for a certain portion it must be dominant by force.
But even if we don’t admit this argument, for ÚOHS it should be a minimum warning that three mobile operators proceed in such strangely similar way.
At the same time, the complaints by the stakeholders (including the mentioned company GTS Novera) show that during negotiations with all operators they encounter very similar obstacles.
Download responsibility to ČTÚ in telecommunications is a fairly common trick with which ÚOHS keeps out of the whole business.
We have seen this in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, it failed to promote the expansion of the rights of ČTÚ in the field of economic competition in telecommunications until the update of the telecommunications law recently approved, despite the fact that, from this, many experts expected the improvement of the situation.
This fact the representatives of ÚOHS must know more than well, but their interests are elsewhere.
It can be done when no one looks.
While we are not aware of it, the functioning of such pseudo-virtual operators remains, some of which even exist in Czech mobile networks.
These are companies that publish their prices lists of mobile telephone services which are public only partially.
These are usually companies that deal with multilevel marketing.
So for example Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and a number of others offer their own mobile phone services.
The pricing lists of these companies usually reach only the predefined people.
The magic lies in the fact that the company facing the operator appears as a classic business client, which orders a large amount of SIM card.
As a major customer then receives special (and other) price offers.
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile telephone operators prohibit a similar prohibition.
"If the cases you are talking about were presented, which we will be interested in, it could be a violation of the contractual conditions, and it could lead to the conclusion of cooperation with that company," said Martina Kemrová.
But it is quite unlikely that such an activity will not reach the ears of the responsible subjects of mobile operators.
Especially in the cases of the 3 mentioned companies you can deal with thousands of customers.
No operator defends himself from such a attitude at the same time.
From the activity of these companies they thus draw a non-indifferent profit and at the same time – unlike real virtual operators – they are not damaged in any way with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns of possible problems: “Law allows such speculations, but only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
They must also accept that the SIM card in their phone is not registered on their behalf, so they cannot have it in full as the usual customers of mobile operators.
But this should be a little strange thing to the CSTU.
In addition, another issue is opened for UOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes to such a attitude, why do they block the creation of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that ÚOHS has strong rights enough to disguise similar activities and if it does not want it will not have to be satisfied with the explanation of the operators who do not have an idea of all this and that their business conditions prohibit it.
When it is no longer expensive
As in the text has been said several times, the entrance of virtual operators to the mobile market has led to a significant drop in prices for services.
At the same time, practically in all countries where traders were born, traditional traders tried more or less to prevent their creation.
The topics they used were practically identical - market too small, the limit too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
But in developed countries in these cases the regulatory bodies have intervened to defend not mobile telephone operators but their customers.
Both with formal measures and with non-formal pressure, then he came to the creation of the first virtual operator and others came to him.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory organs throw the whole case from one to the other as a boiling potato.
For our experience, we cannot get rid of the feeling that the unclearness of the skills in these cases makes it more than comfortable.
Do not throw the sponge.
If the retroscene information is correct and the virtual operator will really soon appear from us, the Czech mobile market will return to the motor.
If one of the operators had agreed to the creation of a virtual mobile operator only hardly ÚOHS could remain impassible to the rejection (discrimination) of other stakeholders.
And we may stop calling at higher prices than the rest of Europe.
The new Czech hymn has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four new versions of the Czech national hymn.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek on the occasion of the Day of recognition of the Czech State presented in a solemn way the new recordings of the national hymn "Kde domov můj".
The new recording of the hymn was made by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available – single with the male or female voice, step of coro and instrumental edition.
The song is directed by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
The authors of the hymn reviews are Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
On the iHNed.cz site you can listen to all four versions.
Bělohlávek considers the Czech national song one of the most begli inni.
He has already told the radio "Český rozhlas" that he has chosen specifically to sing the variants alone, singers with the most representative young voices, which are expressive and popular.
"From the beginning I tried to take care that both and even the coro, have the clear phrase, that the text is well understood, that they are in harmony," he.
The National Hymn will celebrate its 175th anniversary next year.
The song "Kde domov můj" was played for the first time in 1834 on the stage of the Stavovskéh divadlo in the original opera Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl accompanied by the music of František Škroupa.
It has acquired popularity and people have spontaneously made it theirs.
The first strip of the song after the founding of the 1918 Czechoslovakia then became the natural part of the national hymn.
It remains one of the seven national symbols even after the birth of the Autonomous Czech Republic.
