German Günther Bauer in "Flamenco-People" alters the theatrality of some scots to singers, dancers and guitarists on the stage with the least known side of these masters.
With this goal, the photographer offers an original Flamenco iconography, capturing it from various visual angles.
The exhibition, included in the programming of the Month of Flamenco Photography, reflects the international importance of this dance, every day increasing," explains the artist and clarifies that in "Flamenco-People" it might also be common people, but seeing the photos, the observer realizes that they are not the typical images of artists, interpreters or executives on the scene.
These people portrayed "on the road" are "artists able to transmit passion, sadness, joy when they are on stage ... and to catch the audience.
To capture the personality of these great people it is not necessary to bring them back to the scene,
Their personality and character are inherent.
What interested me was creating an intimate atmosphere that allowed me to capture with the camera the personality of the Grandes of the Flamenco.”
With the passion for the festival "Cante de las Minas", Bauer started in 1997 a long journey aimed at retrieving singers, guitarists or dancers using a layer camera.
They are portraits that, due to the type of machine and material, remind the classic photography.
The application of various stylistic techniques breaks with the traditional principles of the image, giving the photo modernity, according to an idea that reflects the Bauer’s own flamenco concept: “A music with very traditional roots that evolves and is able to surprise every day.”
Not the dancing, singing or playing in itself, but the artist’s personality, his character, capable of conquering the audience with his art.
The search for a meeting with the essential elements, with the magic that becomes visible in a certain way of feeling and being, are and have been the constant of this work, exposed these days at the gallery El Fotómata.
Famous Flamenco artists such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, figure in this selection of about seventy portrait artists.
The project has become a sort of flamenco antology, and will soon be published in a book that will collect the portraits exhibited during the exhibition.
The passion for portraits led Bauer to repeat the idea two years ago with "Portraits of Veteran Athletes" ("SportARTproject").
Although in "Flamenco-People" the concept is different, the photographer acknowledges "I like to retrieve people, know them and be able to penetrate for a moment in their lives, whether this is a long or short moment.
I think the portrait is the hardest genre in photography.
You meet or confront people, characters that you sometimes don’t even know or who give you just a few minutes to take the photo.
Beyond these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to concretize my ideas.”
The collection of portraits of contemporary Flamenco, entitled "Flamenco-people" is held at the gallery El Fotómata, at number 20 via de la Mata, parallel to via Alameda de Hercules, and will be open to the public until next 16 October.
