Recidive alcoholism drivers will have to install the "alcoholock"
The Ministry of Internal Affairs requires that drivers with three administrative penalties for excess alcohol in the blood, install in their car the system that prevents the driving of the vehicle in the state of abbreviation or if they do not breathe in the appropriate device.
The measure was announced last June and is already included in the annual report of the General Prosecutor’s Office, according to which it will be a pilot project of one year.
The purpose of this project is the reintegration of the driver, since this will have to attend a rehabilitation course on the road.
In addition to the General Prosecutor's Office for Road Safety, the General Directorate of Traffic (DGT) and the Foundation Institute of Technology for Automotive Safety (FITSA) will participate in this initiative.
According to statistics, between 30% and 75% of drivers more than once by driving in a state of abbreviation then return to driving the car.
Alcoholock would avoid it, because it is a vehicle-connected system that measures the alcohol rate in the breathed air and prevents the car from moving if the driver does not breathe, or when a higher alcohol concentration is detected than permitted.
The cost is more than 1000 euros and it would be on the charges of the sanctioned.
In this regard, a study conducted in the United States in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with such devices allow a reduction of up to 65% of the infringements committed during the first year of introduction.
And in Spain it is calculated that it could save the lives of 115 people a year.
The measure is limited to administrative penalties for two reasons: to stop these behaviors before they become criminal offences.
And to facilitate its development, since the legal reform can be carried out by ordinary means, and, without a doubt, the reform necessary for the criminal proceedings would require an organic law.
However, the device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial solution, although it has already been experimentally introduced in some industrial and public vehicles.
Just tomorrow, the Congress of Deputies will vote on a PSOE initiative in which it proposes to install this system in school buses, as it has already been done in France.
