The Meeting - The Blood Is Back Safe
Héma-Québec celebrated its 10th anniversary yesterday, and its president, Dr. FrancineDécary, had all the reasons to be happy, since Héma-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And above all, it has regained the trust of the public, seriously scared by the infected blood scandal in the years between 1980 and 1990.
As we know, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross transfusion service were infected by the acquired immunodeficiency (HIV) and hepatitis C virus in the 1980s.
Faced with such a drama and the people's protests, the government of Canada conducted in February 1994 a public investigation, led by the judge Horace Krever, aiming to reveal the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to spread recommendations to prevent the repeat of a similar disaster.
While the Krever court was delayed to draw up a report, some provinces established a committee with the aim of conceiving a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, this mandate was executed by the Gélineau Committee.
Following the Gélineau et Krever reports, in Canada two suppliers were created: Héma-Québec to supply Québec and the Société canadienne du sang (Canadian Blood Society) for all the other provinces and the two territories.
In 1998, when Héma-Québec started its activities, just 38% of people said they still had confidence in the donation system in Québec, recalls Dr.ssa Décary.
The situation was mortificating.
Thanks to the continued efforts to improve the safety of blood clots and field research over the following years, we have regained the public’s confidence,” she explains before saying proudly that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of the population of Quebec had already confidence in Héma-Quebec.
Dr. Decary, however, is convinced that “the confidence is something extremely fragile.”
Since its establishment, on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the principle of precaution.
At the time, there was a number of cases in Europe of the human variant of the mad cow, a new manifestation of the disease of Creutzfeldt-Jakob, tells the president of the country since 1998, year of foundation.
"And we didn't know at all if that disease could be transmitted through infected blood.
It was therefore based on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélinau reports, according to which when you have doubts and could a serious disease, in this case the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease that manifests with a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, measures of exclusion are taken.
In April 1999, the blood of those who had spent more than a month in the UK since 1980 was rejected.
Now, for a few years, it has been shown that without any doubt this disease is transmitted through infected blood.
This episode has shown us that it has been meaningful to apply the principle of precaution.”
In 1999, a much more efficient technique for the detection of HIV appeared on the market: nucleic acid (TAN) tests that allow to recognize directly in the blood of donors the presence of the virus and not that of antibodies against it, on which the tests used so far were based.
TANs have allowed to reduce the window period, i.e. from the moment the person has contracted the disease to the one where the first viruses can be detected in the blood thanks to our techniques, the specialist explains.
This period could be reduced to less than a week.
The risk of ignoring the presence of infected donors and of not being able to identify them is thus significantly decreased.
These improvements have allowed to significantly reduce the risk of getting AIDS with a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
In other words, this means that you will need to distribute 12 million blood samples before someone is infected with HIV.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood samples each year, it will take more than 24 years before a HIV case transmitted with a transfusion will occur.
I think today we can feel calm in receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover health, says the head of the direction of Héma-Québec.
“Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
It is never known which pathogen will emerge in the system.
Not later than a year ago the Chikungunya virus appeared on the Island of Réunion which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted into the blood by a insect.
We need to be constantly vigilant,” continues Dr.Ssa Décary before emphasizing that in addition to having safe resources, Héma-Québec must also ensure that it is sufficient.
“The needs are increasing as the population ages.
As the cancer treatments are most aggressive, patients often need a red blood or platinum intake.
The ageing population also has consequences on the number of donors that in average accounts for only 3% of the inhabitants of Quebec acceptable as donors."
However, all healthy people who have reached the age of 18 and meet the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of people offering themselves as donors are not accepted, because they are affected by AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have travelled to a country where the latter is spread, they will be rejected for a period of one year.
“With this 3% we are able to maintain an inventory capable of meeting the needs of hospitals.
The cases of dementia are very rare.
But we need to renew the members of this group of donors as they age and can no longer do donations.
It is now difficult to convince people to donate blood, but above all to keep them back and encourage them to become regular donors.
"Today, life is so frenetic that you hardly find an hour to donate blood," said Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec not only distributes blood samples, but also human tissues, including bone transplants, eye globe heart valves, and skin which is used almost exclusively for severe wear.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before they are deposited at the Héma-Québec which manages the only public blood bank of humboldt cord in Québec.
In the ombelical cord, which once was considered a biomedical deficit, abundant blood rich in stem cells that can serve to cure serious diseases, such as leukemia.
“We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the banking of our thousand cord blood samples and we expect to take more than a thousand each year.
We should start proposing them for transplants at the beginning of next year,” says Dr.Ssa Décary, who describes this cordon blood take practice as very popular.
“Many mothers are disappointed that they can’t have access to you,” as Héma-Québec doesn’t have the necessary means to propose this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Québec.
