The smart car imitates the flight of the calabrone
What could be the best method to develop collision technology if you don’t imitate the sensors of obstacles that are in nature?
For example, the bees.
In the surprising project presented to the CEATEC in Japan, the calabrons gave the initial strategic point to Nissan engineers on how to build the next generation of collision anti-system.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the biomimetic robot BR23C, a robotic mining car equipped with bee properties, with the final purpose of creating a system that can scan all collisions.
Flying bees form their own personal oval space that really resembles our protective shield – explained Kazuhiro Doi, director of the PR technology and research and development industry.
Important is the role of the eyesight of the apes, capable of a vision of 300 degrees in each direction.
The engineers have focused on the idea of telemetry laser to copy the function of apes vision.
The BR23C detects barriers up to two meters away within a radius of 180 degrees, calculates the distance and sends a signal to the board microprocessor that immediately turns it into a command to avoid collision.
In a fraction of a second the robot perceives the obstacle and then, imitating the beef movements, immediately changes direction by turning the wheels to the necessary measure to avoid the accident.
This avoidance maneuver, in a way different from the current system, takes place in a completely instinctive way.
"If not so, the car robot would not know how to react quickly to avoid collisions," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robot car project.
It must react instinctively and immediately because this technology corresponds to the damaging and more internal layer of the protective shield, within which the collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what a bee does to avoid the other bees.
This process must take place in an eye bite.
But unlike the bees, the deviation cannot go up or down or in diagonal, it can only be two-dimensional and in the direction of wheels.
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities available to bees to scan the other bees, the robot, as a possibility available, can rotate on himself, accelerate and slow down.
The BR23C is powered by lithium polymer batteries, lighter and high energy density, which means their duration is greater than the lithium ions.
According to Andoh, the instantaneity of the intelligent reaction is important, not the processing of data or even less the ability to store them.
This robot must process some input in a few seconds and react.
There is no need to store them and respond with intuitive logic based on previous maneuver data, so it uses only a memory of a few dozen Kb.
There is no need for a gigabyte or megabyte memory.
This is the first step towards the development of a technology for immediate collision prevention that, according to Nissan, will be installed on serial vehicles within 10 years.
Further possibility of application can be represented by the unification with the GPS satellite navigation system that avoiding the obstacles on the road leads to the destination.
