MP3 readers under accusation, put the hearing at risk
Listening to high-volume music for a long period of time using portable music devices such as Mp3 readers can cause permanent hearing injury.
This is what the European Commission reports, which in a statement broadcast in Brussels quotes the opinion of the EU Scientific Committee on Emerging and Recently Identified Health Risks (Csrseri), published today.
"From this scientific opinion - it is read in the note - it turns out that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to music with portable music devices weekly for more than an hour a day keeping the high-volume device risks a permanent loss of hearing capacity."
“I am worried that such a large number of young people who frequently use portable music devices and cell phones at high acoustic levels can unconsciously damage their hearing in an irreparable way,” says Meglena Kuneva.
“From scientific findings – the EU official continues – there is a clear risk and we must react quickly.
What’s more important, we need to raise consumer awareness and make this information public.
We must also review the existing control systems, in the light of this scientific opinion, to ensure that they are fully effective and keep the step with the new technology.”
Brussels had asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the large use of portable music devices and the increased number of young people exposed to the noise from them.
"The scientists confirm that there is a reason for concern and the European Commission will now examine together with the Member States and stakeholders what measures could be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable music devices and related equipment."
Currently, there is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable music equipment to 100 dB, but concerns about hearing damage that may result from excessive exposure to such noise sources are increasing.
You can greatly limit these damages by using solutions such as reducing levels and the duration of exposure to noise.
In its opinion, the EU Scientific Committee notes that users of portable music equipment when listening to high volume (more than 89 decibels) music for only 5 hours a week exceed the current limit for maximum permitted noise at workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for longer periods risk a permanent loss of hearing capacity after a period of 5 years.
This would affect 5-10% of users of such devices and their number can be quantified between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
